    <!-- ── HERO GRID ── -->
    <main
      id="main-content"
      role="main"
    >
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-main">
          <div class="byline">By The Internet Outage Atlas Project · March 2026</div>
          <h2 class="hero-headline">The Infrastructure Failures That Reshaped the Internet</h2>
          <p class="hero-subhead">
            "From a mistyped command that took down S3 to a security update that crashed 8.5 million
            Windows machines simultaneously — the modern internet has failed in ways no one
            anticipated."
          </p>
          <div class="hero-body">
            <p>
              The internet has never been more critical to daily life, commerce, and governance. It
              has also never been more fragile. The same concentration of infrastructure that makes
              the web efficient — a handful of cloud providers, a few CDN networks, the universal
              adoption of BGP — creates the conditions for global-scale failures that cascade across
              industries and borders in minutes.
            </p>
            <p>
              This atlas documents fifty-two such incidents, from the 1997 AS7007 route leak that
              briefly made the internet forget its own routes, to the 2024 CrowdStrike Falcon update
              that simultaneously crashed 8.5 million Windows devices at hospitals, airlines, and
              banks around the world. It traces not random accidents but <em>patterns</em> — the recurring
              failure modes of an infrastructure that was never designed to bear this much of the world's
              weight.
            </p>
            <p>
              Read the <a
                href="#timeline"
                class="cta-link"
                >Featured Timeline</a
              >, review the <a
                href="#archive"
                class="cta-link"
                >Incident Archive</a
              >, and study the <a
                href="#taxonomy"
                class="cta-link"
                >Failure Taxonomy</a
              > to understand not just what happened — but why it will happen again.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="column-rule"></div>

        <div class="hero-sidebar">
          <div class="sidebar-title">Key Figures</div>
          <div class="sidebar-fact">
            <div class="sf-number">52</div>
            <div class="sf-label">Incidents Documented</div>
            <div class="sf-note">Curated atlas, version 1</div>
          </div>
          <div class="sidebar-fact">
            <div class="sf-number">8.5M</div>
            <div class="sf-label">Devices in largest incident</div>
            <div class="sf-note">CrowdStrike Falcon, July 2024</div>
          </div>
