      <!-- ── TIMELINE ── -->
      <div class="double-rule"></div>
      <div
        class="sec-masthead reveal"
        id="timeline"
      >
        <div class="sec-kicker">Chapter Three — Featured Timeline</div>
        <h2 class="sec-h">Eight Defining Incidents</h2>
        <p class="sec-intro-p">
          The incidents engineers remember, reference, and build safeguards against — each exposing
          a different class of catastrophic network failure.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-section">
        <div class="tl-entry reveal">
          <div class="tl-year-col"><div class="tl-year">2016</div></div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <div class="tl-hed">Dyn DNS DDoS Attack</div>
            <div class="tl-dek">
              <span>Dyn · Mirai Botnet · Eastern United States</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-red">Critical</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">DNS / DDoS</span>
            </div>
            <p class="tl-body">
              The Mirai botnet — assembled from hundreds of thousands of compromised IoT devices
              including cameras, routers, and DVRs — overwhelmed Dyn's authoritative DNS servers
              with an unprecedented volume of junk requests. Twitter, Spotify, GitHub, Reddit, and
              dozens of other major platforms became unreachable to users across the Eastern United
              States for the better part of a day. The attack exposed the fundamental systemic risk
              created by concentrating critical DNS infrastructure among a small number of
              providers.
            </p>
            <div class="tl-dur">Duration: approximately 8 hours · October 21, 2016</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-entry reveal">
          <div class="tl-year-col"><div class="tl-year">2017</div></div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <div class="tl-hed">AWS S3 US-East-1 Outage</div>
            <div class="tl-dek">
              <span>Amazon Web Services · Northern Virginia Region</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-red">Critical</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">Cloud / Human Error</span>
            </div>
            <p class="tl-body">
              A single mistyped command during routine debugging of the S3 billing system caused an
              engineer to remove far more S3 subsystems than intended. The mistake took down
              thousands of applications — including a significant portion of the internet's visible
              infrastructure — for four hours. The incident permanently reshaped how the cloud
              industry thinks about command execution safety, irreversible operations, and the
              concentration of services in single cloud regions. It remains the industry's canonical
              example of blast radius at cloud scale.
            </p>
            <div class="tl-dur">Duration: approximately 4 hours · February 28, 2017</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-entry reveal">
          <div class="tl-year-col"><div class="tl-year">2020</div></div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <div class="tl-hed">CenturyLink / Level 3 Backbone Outage</div>
            <div class="tl-dek">
              <span>CenturyLink · Lumen Technologies · Global Backbone</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">High Severity</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">BGP / ISP</span>
            </div>
            <p class="tl-body">
              A faulty Flowspec rule, intended to block network abuse, instead blocked BGP itself
              across one of the internet's largest backbone providers. Routers crashed, restarted,
              received the same rule again, and crashed again in a continuous loop — dropping 3.5
              percent of global internet traffic for nearly five hours. The bitter irony: the rule
              meant to protect the network was the thing that destroyed it.
            </p>
            <div class="tl-dur">Duration: approximately 4.5 hours · August 30, 2020</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-entry reveal">
          <div class="tl-year-col"><div class="tl-year">2021</div></div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <div class="tl-hed">Fastly Global Content Delivery Outage</div>
            <div class="tl-dek">
              <span>Fastly · Global CDN Network</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-red">Critical</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">CDN / Edge</span>
            </div>
            <p class="tl-body">
              A software bug, deployed quietly on May 12 but never triggered, lay dormant in
              Fastly's production network until a customer applied a routine configuration change on
              June 8. Within seconds, 85 percent of Fastly's global network began returning errors.
              The BBC, the New York Times, the Guardian, Shopify, and government websites
              disappeared from the web. The incident illustrated the dangerous potential of latent
              software defects in concentrated infrastructure: a single valid configuration change,
              on a single customer's account, took down a significant fraction of the world's
              websites.
            </p>
            <div class="tl-dur">Duration: approximately 1 hour · June 8, 2021</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-entry reveal">
          <div class="tl-year-col"><div class="tl-year">2021</div></div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <div class="tl-hed">Facebook Global Blackout</div>
            <div class="tl-dek">
              <span>Meta Platforms · Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp, Messenger</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-red">Critical</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">BGP / Platform</span>
            </div>
            <p class="tl-body">
              During routine backbone maintenance, a configuration change was pushed that withdrew
              all of Facebook's BGP route announcements. The company's DNS infrastructure — which
              the outside world needed to reach Facebook's servers — became invisible to the global
              routing table. Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp, and Messenger vanished from the internet
              simultaneously. Engineers who might have fixed the problem remotely found that the
              same BGP withdrawal had made their internal tools inaccessible. Recovery required
              physical entry into data centers and manual authentication without working remote
              access systems. Approximately $47 billion in market capitalization evaporated over six
              hours.
            </p>
            <div class="tl-dur">Duration: approximately 6 hours · October 4, 2021</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-entry reveal">
          <div class="tl-year-col"><div class="tl-year">2024</div></div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <div class="tl-hed">CrowdStrike Falcon Global Outage</div>
            <div class="tl-dek">
              <span>CrowdStrike · Microsoft Windows · Worldwide</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-red">Critical</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">Software Supply Chain</span>
            </div>
            <p class="tl-body">
              A faulty configuration file included in a routine CrowdStrike Falcon security sensor
              update caused kernel-level crashes across an estimated 8.5 million Windows devices
              worldwide. Airlines could not process passengers. Hospitals reverted to paper records.
              Banks closed systems. Government agencies lost access to critical infrastructure.
              Unlike a server outage — correctable from a control plane — each of the 8.5 million
              machines required individual manual intervention to remove the defective file and
              restore operation. Full recovery took ten days. The incident stands as the largest
              software-induced mass systems failure in recorded history.
            </p>
            <div class="tl-dur">Duration: recovery spanning 10 days · July 19, 2024</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-entry reveal">
          <div class="tl-year-col"><div class="tl-year">2025</div></div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <div class="tl-hed">AWS DynamoDB DNS Failure — US-East-1</div>
            <div class="tl-dek">
              <span>Amazon Web Services · Northern Virginia Region</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-red">Critical</span>
              <span class="tl-tag tag-ink">Cloud / DNS</span>
            </div>
            <p class="tl-body">
              DNS resolution for DynamoDB — the NoSQL database service that underpins thousands of
              AWS-hosted applications — failed in the US-East-1 region, making it impossible for
              applications to locate the database even though all the data stored within it remained
              intact. Disney+, Delta Air Lines, Reddit, Robinhood, Roblox, and more than seventy
              AWS-dependent services went dark for the better part of a business day. The incident
              illustrated a bitter paradox: the data was fine; no one could reach it. A fifteen-hour
              DNS failure defeated the resilience of the underlying storage layer entirely.
            </p>
            <div class="tl-dur">Duration: approximately 15 hours · October 20, 2025</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ── ARCHIVE ── -->
      <div class="double-rule"></div>
      <div
        class="sec-masthead reveal"
        id="archive"
      >
        <div class="sec-kicker">Chapter Four — Incident Archive</div>
        <h2 class="sec-h">The Broader Corpus</h2>
        <p class="sec-intro-p">
          Supporting incidents from the full 52-incident atlas — each clipped for the record,
          annotated for the lesson.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="archive-section">
        <div class="clipping-grid">
          <div class="clipping reveal">
            <div class="clp-date">February 2008</div>
            <div class="clp-cat">BGP Route Hijack</div>
            <div class="clp-hed">Pakistan Telecom Blacks Out YouTube for the World</div>
            <div class="clp-rule"></div>
            <div class="clp-body">
              An attempt by Pakistan Telecom to block YouTube domestically resulted in a BGP route
              announcement that escaped containment, briefly making YouTube unreachable globally.
              The incident demonstrated that BGP — the protocol linking all of the internet's
              networks — has no inherent scope enforcement. A route meant for one country became a
              route for everywhere.
            </div>
            <div class="clp-lesson">
              The lesson: BGP propagates without judgment. Filters are not optional.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="clipping reveal">
            <div class="clp-date">April 2011</div>
            <div class="clp-cat">Cloud Infrastructure</div>
            <div class="clp-hed">AWS EC2 Failure Exposes Limits of Availability Zone Isolation</div>
            <div class="clp-rule"></div>
            <div class="clp-body">
              A network upgrade misrouted Elastic Block Store traffic, causing EBS volumes to become
              unavailable across the US-East-1 region. Reddit, Quora, Foursquare, and others
              dependent on EC2 in a single availability zone went offline for hours or days. The
              event established that AZ-level redundancy provides no protection against
              control-plane cascade failures.
            </div>
            <div class="clp-lesson">
              The lesson: Multi-region is not optional for critical workloads.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="clipping reveal">
            <div class="clp-date">June 2019</div>
            <div class="clp-cat">BGP Route Leak</div>
            <div class="clp-hed">
              Verizon Route Leak Disrupts 15 Percent of Global Internet Traffic
            </div>
            <div class="clp-rule"></div>
            <div class="clp-body">
              An unfiltered route table from a small ISP using BGP Optimizer software was accepted
              by Verizon and propagated widely, misdirecting enormous volumes of traffic.
              Cloudflare, Facebook, and Google were all impacted. The incident demonstrated that
              major carriers' willingness to accept unvalidated routes from small networks creates
              systemic exposure.
            </div>
            <div class="clp-lesson">
              The lesson: Transit filtering must be enforced upstream, not assumed.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="clipping reveal">
            <div class="clp-date">December 2020</div>
            <div class="clp-cat">Authentication Failure</div>
            <div class="clp-hed">Google Auth Outage Renders All Google Services Inaccessible</div>
            <div class="clp-rule"></div>
            <div class="clp-body">
              A quota enforcement error during a migration of Google's authentication infrastructure
              caused a 47-minute outage affecting Gmail, YouTube, Drive, and every other Google
              service simultaneously. The underlying data was unaffected; users simply could not
              authenticate to access it. A brief authentication failure produced a complete platform
              blackout.
            </div>
            <div class="clp-lesson">
              The lesson: Authentication is an all-or-nothing chokepoint.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="clipping reveal">
            <div class="clp-date">July 2021</div>
            <div class="clp-cat">DNS / CDN</div>
            <div class="clp-hed">Akamai DNS Outage Silences FedEx, Airlines, and Major Banks</div>
            <div class="clp-rule"></div>
            <div class="clp-body">
              A configuration update triggered a software bug in Akamai's Edge DNS product, causing
              a 83-minute outage affecting enterprises including FedEx, United Airlines, UPS, and
              Capital One. The incident revealed that even institutions operating substantial
              private infrastructure are exposed by DNS concentration at major CDN providers.
            </div>
            <div class="clp-lesson">
              The lesson: DNS dependency extends further than most operators realize.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="clipping reveal">
            <div class="clp-date">July 2022</div>
            <div class="clp-cat">Telecom Core Failure</div>
            <div class="clp-hed">Rogers Canada: 12 Million Without Service, Including 911</div>
            <div class="clp-rule"></div>
            <div class="clp-body">
              The removal of a critical control filter during Phase 6 of a network upgrade sent
              misdirected traffic flooding into the Rogers core network. With no overload protection
              in place, the entire core collapsed — leaving 12 million Canadians without mobile
              service, internet access, and — most critically — 911 emergency service for 26 hours.
              Engineers could not access remote systems to diagnose or remediate the problem.
            </div>
            <div class="clp-lesson">
              The lesson: Core networks require overload protection by default, not as an
              afterthought.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ── TAXONOMY ── -->
      <div class="double-rule"></div>
      <div
        class="sec-masthead reveal"
        id="taxonomy"
      >
        <div class="sec-kicker">Chapter Five — Failure Taxonomy</div>
        <h2 class="sec-h">How the Internet Fails</h2>
        <p class="sec-intro-p">
          Six recurring failure categories — each with its own trigger mechanisms, propagation
          patterns, and characteristic blast radius.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="taxonomy-section">
        <div class="taxon-list">
          <div class="txn-entry">
            <div class="txn-term">
              <div class="txn-word">DNS</div>
              <div class="txn-pos">noun, failure class 01</div>
              <div class="txn-n">Domain Name System</div>
            </div>
            <div class="txn-def">
              <p class="txn-def-text">
                The address book of the internet fails to resolve domain names to IP addresses.
                Servers remain operational, but users cannot discover their locations. The failure
                mode is total, invisible, and affects every user simultaneously — appearing, from
                the outside, as if the service itself has vanished.
              </p>
              <p class="txn-trigger">
                <strong>Common triggers:</strong> Volumetric DDoS attacks against resolvers, software
                defects in DNS server applications activated by configuration changes, quota enforcement
                errors in cloud DNS infrastructure.
              </p>
              <div class="txn-examples">
                <span class="txn-ex">Dyn DDoS 2016</span><span class="txn-ex">Akamai DNS 2021</span
                ><span class="txn-ex">AWS DynamoDB 2025</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="txn-entry">
            <div class="txn-term">
              <div class="txn-word">BGP / Routing</div>
              <div class="txn-pos">noun, failure class 02</div>
              <div class="txn-n">Border Gateway Protocol</div>
            </div>
            <div class="txn-def">
              <p class="txn-def-text">
                The routing protocol that connects the world's networks to each other is corrupted
                by leaked or incorrect route announcements. Traffic is sent to incorrect
                destinations, or routed into a black hole. The failure may be localized to a region
                or global, depending on how widely the invalid route propagates.
              </p>
              <p class="txn-trigger">
                <strong>Common triggers:</strong> Route leaks from small ISPs without proper filters,
                BGP Optimizer software misbehavior, government-ordered route announcements that escape
                containment, faulty Flowspec rules issued to routers.
              </p>
              <div class="txn-examples">
                <span class="txn-ex">Pakistan YouTube 2008</span><span class="txn-ex"
                  >Verizon 2019</span
                ><span class="txn-ex">Facebook 2021</span><span class="txn-ex"
                  >CenturyLink 2020</span
                >
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="txn-entry">
            <div class="txn-term">
              <div class="txn-word">CDN / Edge</div>
              <div class="txn-pos">noun, failure class 03</div>
              <div class="txn-n">Content Delivery Network</div>
            </div>
            <div class="txn-def">
              <p class="txn-def-text">
                Content delivery networks, which serve the majority of web traffic, fail
                simultaneously across their distributed infrastructure. Thousands of websites go
                dark even though their origin servers remain fully operational — the delivery layer,
                not the content itself, has failed.
              </p>
              <p class="txn-trigger">
                <strong>Common triggers:</strong> Latent software bugs activated by valid configuration
                changes, errors in configuration update systems, DDoS mitigation systems that inadvertently
                block legitimate traffic.
              </p>
              <div class="txn-examples">
                <span class="txn-ex">Fastly 2021</span><span class="txn-ex">Akamai 2021</span><span
                  class="txn-ex">Cloudflare 2025</span
                >
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="txn-entry">
            <div class="txn-term">
              <div class="txn-word">Cloud Control Plane</div>
              <div class="txn-pos">noun, failure class 04</div>
              <div class="txn-n">Cloud Management Layer</div>
            </div>
            <div class="txn-def">
              <p class="txn-def-text">
                The management infrastructure that orchestrates cloud services — launching
                instances, allocating storage, routing between services — fails. All data stored
                within the affected cloud remains intact, but no application can reach it, and no
                new resources can be created. The outage is complete and total without any data
                loss.
              </p>
              <p class="txn-trigger">
                <strong>Common triggers:</strong> Configuration changes to foundational services, quota
                enforcement system errors, authentication infrastructure failures during migration operations.
              </p>
              <div class="txn-examples">
                <span class="txn-ex">AWS S3 2017</span><span class="txn-ex">Google Auth 2020</span
                ><span class="txn-ex">Azure Storage 2014</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="txn-entry">
            <div class="txn-term">
              <div class="txn-word">Software Supply Chain</div>
              <div class="txn-pos">noun, failure class 05</div>
              <div class="txn-n">Dependency Propagation</div>
            </div>
            <div class="txn-def">
              <p class="txn-def-text">
                A software update, library change, or supply-chain component introduces a defect
                that propagates automatically to every system that depends on it — simultaneously
                and without any further action by the affected organizations. The key characteristic
                is the combination of ubiquity, automaticity, and simultaneity of the failure.
              </p>
              <p class="txn-trigger">
                <strong>Common triggers:</strong> Routine update deployments without adequate staged rollout,
                kernel-level security software with privileged system access, certificate expiry in widely
                distributed libraries, malicious modifications to widely used packages.
              </p>
              <div class="txn-examples">
                <span class="txn-ex">NotPetya 2017</span><span class="txn-ex">CrowdStrike 2024</span
                >
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="txn-entry">
            <div class="txn-term">
              <div class="txn-word">Telecom Backbone</div>
              <div class="txn-pos">noun, failure class 06</div>
              <div class="txn-n">Tier-1 Infrastructure</div>
            </div>
            <div class="txn-def">
              <p class="txn-def-text">
                Tier-1 carriers and backbone ISPs that carry large fractions of global internet
                traffic fail, affecting all of their downstream transit customers simultaneously. As
                these providers form the substrate upon which the entire internet's routing is
                built, their failures propagate widely and recover slowly.
              </p>
              <p class="txn-trigger">
                <strong>Common triggers:</strong> Errors during scheduled maintenance windows, faulty
                routing protocol configuration rules, physical fiber damage, core network overload cascading
                through shared infrastructure without protective rate limits.
              </p>
              <div class="txn-examples">
                <span class="txn-ex">CenturyLink 2020</span><span class="txn-ex">Rogers 2022</span
                ><span class="txn-ex">CenturyLink 911 2018</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ── BLAST RADIUS ── -->
      <div class="double-rule"></div>
      <div
        class="sec-masthead reveal"
        id="blast"
      >
        <div class="sec-kicker">Chapter Six — Blast Radius</div>
        <h2 class="sec-h">How Failures Spread</h2>
        <p class="sec-intro-p">
          The scale of an internet outage is determined by concentration of shared dependencies.
          Foundational failures produce cascading collapse.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="blast-section">
        <div class="blast-inset">
          <div class="blast-inset-title">Failure Propagation Model — Illustrated</div>
          <div class="blast-inset-sub">
            From contained local failure to internet-scale cascading collapse — four levels of blast
            radius.
          </div>
          <div class="blast-row">
            <div class="blast-item">
              <div class="blast-circle b1"><span class="blast-num">I</span></div>
              <div class="blast-label-title">Local Failure</div>
              <div class="blast-label-desc">
                A single server or service fails. Only its direct users are affected. Recovery is
                rapid and contained.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="blast-item">
              <div class="blast-circle b2"><span class="blast-num">II</span></div>
              <div class="blast-label-title">Provider Failure</div>
              <div class="blast-label-desc">
                A cloud region or CDN fails. All dependent customers lose service simultaneously,
                regardless of their own code quality.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="blast-item">
              <div class="blast-circle b3"><span class="blast-num red">III</span></div>
              <div class="blast-label-title">Shared Dependency</div>
              <div class="blast-label-desc">
                DNS or BGP fails. Every service that depends on it — across all providers — fails
                simultaneously and completely.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="blast-item">
              <div class="blast-circle b4"><span class="blast-num red">IV</span></div>
              <div class="blast-label-title">Cascading Collapse</div>
              <div class="blast-label-desc">
                Failure in one system overloads adjacent systems. Retry storms and routing
                instability compound into self-reinforcing collapse.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ── METHODOLOGY ── -->
      <div class="double-rule"></div>
      <div
        class="sec-masthead reveal"
        id="methodology"
      >
        <div class="sec-kicker">Chapter Seven — Methodology and Sources</div>
        <h2 class="sec-h">How This Atlas Was Built</h2>
        <p class="sec-intro-p"></p>
      </div>
      <div class="method-section">
        <div class="method-col">
          <h4>Inclusion Criteria</h4>
          <p>
            Incidents are included if they meet one or more of the following criteria: significant
            U.S. user impact, classification as a novel or landmark failure mode, or strong value as
            a case study in infrastructure resilience. "Significant" is defined as disruption
            lasting more than fifteen minutes affecting more than one major service or platform.
          </p>
          <p>
            Excluded are: minor degradations, incidents verifiable only through social media
            reports, and cases with insufficient primary-source documentation to verify key factual
            claims.
          </p>
          <h4 style="margin-top:1.5rem;">Handling Disputed Details</h4>
          <p>
            Where authoritative sources conflict, this atlas uses the most conservative figure and
            notes the dispute. Financial impact estimates are treated as rough orders of magnitude
            only and are never presented as precise measurements. Attribution of malicious intent is
            never stated without a clear official record as source.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-col">
          <h4>Source Hierarchy</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Company postmortems and official incident reports</li>
            <li>Regulatory filings (FCC, CRTC, and equivalent bodies)</li>
            <li>
              Technical analyses by BGP monitoring services (Cloudflare Radar, RIPE NCC, RouteViews)
            </li>
            <li>Investigative journalism with technical depth and primary sources cited</li>
            <li>Peer-reviewed research and major conference proceedings (USENIX, SIGCOMM)</li>
          </ul>
          <h4 style="margin-top:1.5rem;">Scope and Coverage</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>52-incident curated atlas, version 1</li>
            <li>13-incident canonical core for the featured timeline</li>
            <li>56-incident watchlist for potential version 2 expansion</li>
            <li>Temporal scope: year 2000 through March 2026</li>
            <li>Geographic focus: incidents with significant U.S. user impact prioritized</li>
            <li>No real-time monitoring component; this is a historical record</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>

